title: For Sale:  NIB CZC Pro Tek I "Ultimate Carry"
postcontent:
Date of test fire target is 5/5/15.  I already have an SDP, but this is still a "wow" gun.  This new-in-box Pro Tek I is built off the PCR, which is lighter weight and slightly smaller than the P-01 (SDP or Pro Tek II, the latter of which is not yet back in production).

This is a cash-only sale please, no trades.  Also, I cut the price some but this means it's firm.  

This is a new, fantastic carry gun at cost.  Some people say you should not carry an expensive gun as it would be taken away if you ever had to use it.  In my view, that would be the least of anyone's concerns!  

Here is what the new, new version offers:  "On the new build we install the short reset disconnector and fitment for the decocker mechanism.  We install the new style heinie straight 8 night sight and the thin checkered aluminum grips."

More CZ info:

Starting with the light weight 9mm Compact PCR, we have created a new carry model pistol.

We created what we consider the Ultimate CZ Compact Carry gun.
The gun uses the CZ SA DA Competition hammer in a decocker format
Single Action trigger at approx 3.5-4.0 lbs Crisp and smooth, Double Action at a smooth 7 / 8 Lbs
Firing pin block are left intact but smoothed and Polished. Overall gun has been de horned
for a smooth feel, decocker has been cut back to be less obtrusive.
Features:

Heinie Straight 8.
Tritium Front Sight.
Octagon slide.
Flat top slide.
Slide Relief Cut on front of Slide.
Slim Checkered Aluminum Grips panels.
Trigger job.
Custom SA DA Decocker Hammer.
Short Reset Trigger.
De-burred external surfaces.
Black Polycoat Finish.
Blued Slide.
Has one 16 rd and one 14 rd. mag

The Pro Tek Story:

The story behind the development of the Pro-Tek models starts like this: Angus always carried a sub-compact model.  Our facility is located in a commercial area and we frequently work the weekends playing catch up mostly. It was a Saturday afternoon Angus heard a banging thought it was someone stopping by with a parts delivery. After opening the door in the warehouse he sees across the street a car with an individual pointing a shot gun at him. Angus drew his sub-compact and took a sight picture realizing now that the short sight radius wouldn’t forgive any inaccuracy in sight alignment he thought better and didn’t return fire. Angus is a well trained in tactical scenarios and also a quite accomplished shooter. If Angus didn’t feel good about the shot could someone with less training make that shot?

The decision was made to go to the Compact models for the additional sight radius and more capacity. The problem was they weren’t comfortable to carry. So the ideas were brewing at that point. We have done lots of 1911 work in the past and melting down the pistol is quite common. We also know that removing some of the mass of the slide will allow the slide to move faster. This allows for quicker recovery and less mass reciprocating. Novak style sights were added for their low drag and resistance to snagging on clothing. We used tritium inserts in the sights since most encounters aren’t in bright light but in lower light situations.

What do we do to the Pro-Tek models? Why do they cost so much? We start with the PCR or P01 model we debur or dehorn the slide frame and controls. We blend the aluminum grips to match the frame so there are no edges to bother the skin or body. To reduce slide mass we CNC cut 45's and flat top, then surface grind for a perfect smooth finish to reduce mass. We machine a Novak cut into the slide for the Champion Extreme Duty night sights. We install a custom made Trijicon front sight. We open up the magwell to make reloads smoother and easier. Most of this work is done by hand (blending) then we send the frames out for hard anodizing. The process takes about 8 hours or so. The result in my opinion one of the most comfortable and easiest to shoot carry guns available.

This started out life as a 6.5" barreled revolver with a standard fluted cylinder. After hundreds of dollars later and a few weeks at the S&W factory Performance Center, it was transformed. away my Father recieved it..The Colt was wrapped in a old rag, stowed away in a

it was a 95% plus.  There is a very small gigger chip on the inside bottom grip as shown.  (Sorry for the Crappy photos)

  The gun dealers said it is worth $800.00 to $1,100. They offered me $700.00

title: For Sale:  REMINGTON RAND MODEL 1911A1  Late 1945 Production/Complete Rig C&R
postcontent: This is a great pistol for the collector of WWII handguns or 1911 pistols.it is a very late production Remington Rand that was manufactured close to the end of production in 1945. Completely original, this pistol has the correct light grey parkerized finish that was used in the last months of production (after about serial number 2,380,000). All parts are correct/original and the condition is very hard to beat, this pistol is nearly new! It has the correct late serrated slide lock, late 8-rib mainspring housing, HS contract barrel, correct hammer, correct Keyes Fibre grips, etc. The finish is completely original with the "P" proofs matching in size/shape and showing the characteristic burnishing, having been stamped after parkerizing. The ordnance crossed cannons, FJA inspectors marking, and the serial number also show the stamped after finish, burnished appearance. As expected, the bullet ramp is bright, milled after finish. The original light grey parkerized finish shows a few normal handling marks, but is one of those rare military 1911A1's that has almost no takedown scratch. The original finish rates about 98% and is free of any rust or pitting. The grips are in excellent condition as well with little wear and no cracks, chips or gouges. The mechanics appear to be in perfect working order and the bore is mirror bright with sharp rifling. This exceptional pistol comes with three original, late WWII General Shaver contract magazines as well as an unissued/original Boyt 45 marked holster w/ lanyard, original pistol belt, WWII double mag pouch (Boyle 1942), and original late war style Carlisle bandage in the original first aid pouch (Brede Inc. 1945). This pistol is serial number 2445758...the last 1911A1 produced by Remington Rand was 2465139...

When a round is in the chamber, the ejector pops out of the slide, exposing a red strip just behind the ejection port. title: For Sale:  2nd Generation Colt of John Barraclough Engraved ‘Liberty & Justice’ AMAZING revolver with Case
postcontent:
Make: Colt’s PT. F.A. MFG. Co.

Model: 2nd Generation Single Action Army

Year of Manufacture: 1963

Caliber: .45 Colt

Action Type: Single Action Revolver with Side Loading-Gate Cylinders 

Markings: The left side of the barrel is marked “1863 – ARIZIONA TERRITORIAL CENTENNIAL – 1963”. The left side of the frame is marked “PAT. SEPT. 19, 1871 / JULY, 72 JAN. 19, 75” and with a Rampant Colt logo. The top of the barrel is marked “COLT’S PT. F.A. MFG. Co. HARTFORD CT. U.S.A.” The right side of the barrel is marked “COLT SINGLE ACTION ARMY .45”. The left side of the trigger guard is marked with a Triangle “VP” proof and “V”. The right side of the trigger guard is marked with a “P”. The underside of the frame and insides of the trigger guard and backstrap are marked “373AC”. The rear face of the cylinder sports a Rampant Colt logo and the front face is marked “373”. 

Barrel Length: about 5 ½”

Sights / Optics: The front sights are quarter round blades set into the barrel. The rear sights are “U” grooves milled into the top straps.

Stock Configuration & Condition: The two piece Mother of Pearl grips sport an engraved Rampant Colt medallion on each panel. Natural variations in the material are apparent on both panels. The grips exhibit almost no evidence of handling and both medallions exhibit hand engraved backgrounds. The grips rate in about Excellent overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Nickel

Finish Originality: Refinished

Bore Condition: The bore is bright and the rifling is sharp. There is no erosion in the bore.

Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 97% of its metal finish. Almost no signs of handling are visible, except an area of finish thinning is visible on the right side of the frame, extending to the trigger guard. The screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. Overall, this handgun rates in about Fine to Excellent condition.

Mechanics: The action functions correctly. I did not fire this handgun. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: These pistol is housed in a walnut display case with a Colt logo burned into the lid. The exterior surfaces exhibit multiple marks in the finish and shallow marks into the wood. The interior of the case is lined in burgundy velveteen and has two form fit compartments. The velveteen exhibits shallow marks from contact with the pistol. The case is in Very Good condition.

M Assessment: This is a lovely 2nd Generation Colt Single Action Army pistols in a display case. The revolver is part of the Arizona Territory Centennial series manufactured in 1963, and were subsequently engraved by Master Engraver John Barraclough in 1999. The art work expresses a “Cowboys and Indian” theme in the “cattle brand” style. The pistol sports a spear and tomahawk on the right side of the frame and an eagle head on the recoil shield. An Arizona Ranger star is present on the top of the strap with icons of the West represented on the rear of the backstrap. A turtle and a rattle snake appear on the cylinder.The butt of the pistol which reads “LIBERTY”. The remainder of the artwork on the pistol is bold and the backgrounds are meticulously stippled. The bright nickel finish compliments the natural Mother of Pearl grips which look striking set into the burgundy lining of the case. This is a spectacular, one of a kind set of 2nd Generation Single Action Army pistol, magnificently engraved by Master Engraver John Barraclough which will be a highlight of any high end Colt collection (particularly in the Arizona Territory.)

This is a great option to shoot two great calibers, and do it without spending money on two uppers, and two optics. The barrel can be changed in less than 2 minutes. LMT is one of the best in the business, on par or better than any AR manufacturer. Upper was cerakoted FDE.

- MRP upper new without the brake is $1250-$1400 (never fired)
- 8.5" .300 blk barrel assembly Noveske barrel w/ AAC 51T Brakeout 2.0 ($800)

- 12.5" complete piston barrel and assembly w/ POF roller cam upgrades (fired for function) w/ piston LMT BCG are $750-$950 w/ upgrades
- Gas buster charging handle (for suppressed fire) new, $115

The 10.5" 5.56 is DI LMT barrel w/ a AAC 51T Brake. never fired

The 8.5 .300 BLK is a Noveske barrel custom made for use w/ a MRP platform.

The 12.5" piston barrel assembly was upgraded with a POF rollercam upgrade which has significantly smoothed carrier travel. And the plug on the piston is not the standard plug it is the upgraded version, that is offered by LMT's, that is for suppressed and unsuppressed fire. The difference between the standard plug and the upgraded plug is the standard plug only has one side that is open for fire the other is closed. Where as with the suppressed and non-suppressed plug there are holes on both sides of the plug to better regulate gas flow for when you are running either non-suppressed or suppressed fire. (The piston configuration was used with my other MRP, ~120 rounds to function test it.)

Package as is value is easily $3k, I know I'm not going to get $3k so asking $2.5k cash (OBO), open to trades. Going to put this on GB first, but thought I'd list locally first.

- 12.5" .223/5.56 LMT Barrel piston w/ LMT piston BCG

The MRP was cerakoted FDE by WAR Rifles, they did a great job, no blemishes.

I will consider trades, but really only interested in SCAR 16 or SCAR 17 in FDE. Let me know what you have, worse I can say is no thanks.
